INSERT INTO companion_content
  (trigger_id, headline, in_app_message, learn_more, escalation_text,
   share_card, sources, design_note, in_app_message_path_b, in_app_message_path_c)
VALUES (
  'AG-022',
  'Freezer stash: what a healthy buffer actually looks like',
  'A lot of pumping moms feel like they need a huge freezer stash to feel secure. The anxiety about the stash can take over. Here''s a more grounded way to think about it.',
  'A freezer stash is a safety buffer — not a measure of success or how much you love your baby. Most families don''t need a massive stash, and obsessing over building it can lead to oversupply issues.

A functional buffer: 3–5 days of your baby''s daily intake is a realistic and adequate working stash for most families. At 8 weeks, a baby typically takes 3–4 oz per feed and feeds 8–10 times per day — roughly 25–30 oz/day. A buffer of 75–150 oz is genuinely protective without requiring heroic pumping effort.

How to build it without burning out: if you''re consistently making slightly more than your baby needs, freeze the daily surplus rather than adding extra sessions. One extra pump session per day after the first morning feed (typically the highest-output session) is a sustainable approach.

Oversupply is its own problem: moms who pump aggressively beyond demand can develop chronic engorgement, recurrent plugged ducts, and mastitis. Bigger is not always better.

Storage math: milk in the back of a chest freezer at 0°F keeps for up to 12 months. Label each bag with date and volume. Rotate older bags to the front.

Sources: CDC human milk storage guidelines; ABM Protocol #32.',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  'CDC milk storage guidelines; ABM Protocol #32',
  NULL,
  NULL,
  NULL
) ON CONFLICT (trigger_id) DO UPDATE SET
